WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.690 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:21.930 --> 00:00:23.230
&gt;&gt; David Mao: OK.

00:00:23.230 --> 00:00:24.530
Well, good afternoon again.

00:00:24.530 --> 00:00:25.830
My name is David Mao.

00:00:25.830 --> 00:00:29.110
And I was supposed to be welcoming
the new ambassador from Mexico

00:00:29.110 --> 00:00:32.120
to the United States, but he has
been detained across the street.

00:00:32.120 --> 00:00:36.010 position:56%
And as we at the Library of
Congress know, Congress comes first.

00:00:36.010 --> 00:00:37.310
[ Laughter ]

00:00:37.310 --> 00:00:39.350
So I'm told that he will
be joining us momentarily.

00:00:39.350 --> 00:00:41.150
So we'll go ahead and get started,

00:00:41.150 --> 00:00:45.900
and if Ambassador Sada
Solana is able to join us,

00:00:45.900 --> 00:00:51.160
he will at the end of the program.

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:53.750
It's my pleasure, of
course, to have the ability

00:00:53.750 --> 00:00:56.210
to celebrate something here
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:56.210 --> 00:00:58.030
And, you know, we celebrate
things all the time.

00:00:58.030 --> 00:01:00.630 position:56%
But this is particularly significant

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:03.090
because so many people have
worked so hard on this.

00:01:03.090 --> 00:01:07.000 position:56%
We're here to celebrate, of
course, the Spanish language version

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.640
of a very important tool
of the Library of Congress,

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:13.610
and that is the website
that talks about Mexico

00:01:13.610 --> 00:01:16.730
and its relationship
with the United States.

00:01:16.730 --> 00:01:19.640
We've had that information
available for quite some time

00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:24.510
and we've been working even harder
to make it available in Spanish.

00:01:24.510 --> 00:01:27.290
And so that's what we're here
for today, and I'm very excited

00:01:27.290 --> 00:01:28.960
that we're able to do that.

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:32.980
I think all of you know here
what's available on the website.

00:01:32.980 --> 00:01:35.850
It includes a lot of
primary source information

00:01:35.850 --> 00:01:39.840 position:56%
from the Library's collections,
whether it be prints or photographs,

00:01:39.840 --> 00:01:44.580
manuscripts, pages from rare books,
things like that, all digitized.

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:49.030 position:56%
And perhaps more importantly it
includes text and commentary to talk

00:01:49.030 --> 00:01:51.590
about this historic period
that defined the border

00:01:51.590 --> 00:01:55.180
between the United States and
Mexico, and really was very,

00:01:55.180 --> 00:01:57.270
very instrumental in
defining the relationship

00:01:57.270 --> 00:01:59.550
between our two countries early on.

00:01:59.550 --> 00:02:03.800 position:56%
And so I think it's really fantastic
that we're able to now provide

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:06.420
that information in Spanish.

00:02:06.420 --> 00:02:09.220
I have to congratulate
Georgette, of course,

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:12.750
as the chief of the Hispanic
division for leading the team.

00:02:12.750 --> 00:02:14.050
And where's Barbara?

00:02:14.050 --> 00:02:15.350
I saw Barbara somewhere.

00:02:15.350 --> 00:02:16.650
Oh, right.

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:17.950
Sorry. Right in front
of me, Barbara --

00:02:17.950 --> 00:02:19.250
[ Laughter ]

00:02:19.250 --> 00:02:20.550
-- former Mexican specialist.

00:02:20.550 --> 00:02:22.690
And Juan Manuel and,
Tracy, where are all of you?

00:02:22.690 --> 00:02:24.000
Oh, Tracy's over here.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:25.480
And certainly I saw Everett
[assumed spelling] somewhere --

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:29.360
oh, there you go -- former
head of the Reading Room.

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:33.470 position:56%
All of you working together over the
-- how long has it been, actually?

00:02:33.470 --> 00:02:34.770
&gt;&gt; Eight years.

00:02:34.770 --> 00:02:36.070
&gt;&gt; David Mao: Eight --

00:02:36.070 --> 00:02:37.370 position:56%
&gt;&gt; That we've been working together?

00:02:37.370 --> 00:02:38.670
&gt;&gt; David Mao: No, no,
on this Spanish --

00:02:38.670 --> 00:02:39.970
[ Laughter ]

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:41.270
-- language -- [laughs].

00:02:41.270 --> 00:02:42.570
&gt;&gt; The Spanish part?

00:02:42.570 --> 00:02:43.870
Six years.

00:02:43.870 --> 00:02:45.170
&gt;&gt; David Mao: OK, six years.

00:02:45.170 --> 00:02:46.470
So that's how long it took
with all of these people,

00:02:46.470 --> 00:02:47.770
a couple of interns
thrown in there, of course,

00:02:47.770 --> 00:02:49.250
and certainly collaboration
with a lot of our colleagues

00:02:49.250 --> 00:02:50.710
at the Library -- across
the Library.

00:02:50.710 --> 00:02:52.500
And many of you are
sitting here in the audience

00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:55.720
to celebrate this terrific
launching.

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:57.670
So congratulations to all of you.

00:02:57.670 --> 00:03:03.150
Welcome to -- all of you to
the Hispanic Reading Room.

00:03:03.150 --> 00:03:04.450
Is there anything else
I need to say?

00:03:04.450 --> 00:03:05.750
No, I'm delaying.

00:03:05.750 --> 00:03:07.050
I was hoping that the
ambassador would come in --

00:03:07.050 --> 00:03:08.350
[ Laughter ]

00:03:08.350 --> 00:03:09.940
-- so that I could properly
introduce him, but we'll have

00:03:09.940 --> 00:03:11.240
to save that until the end.

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:14.240
So let's turn it over now to
Georgette to give us a little talk

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:15.670
about it, and then we'll carry on.

00:03:15.670 --> 00:03:17.470
So thank you.

00:03:17.470 --> 00:03:24.730
[ Applause ]

00:03:24.730 --> 00:03:30.270
&gt;&gt; Georgette Dorn: An ambassador's
time is never his own, as you know.

00:03:30.270 --> 00:03:36.920
We are very honored to have you all
here in this historic Reading Room.

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:39.120
As you know, this is the first
foreign area reading room

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:42.670
of the Library of Congress,
which opened its doors in 1939,

00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:45.910
and it's one of three
still in the same place.

00:03:45.910 --> 00:03:49.670
The others are the Rare Book
Room and the Main Reading Room.

00:03:49.670 --> 00:03:54.300
The Mexican Revolution was a very
important event in the history

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:56.120
of both Mexico and
the United States.

00:03:56.120 --> 00:04:01.640 position:56%
It changed the border, the frontera,
forever between the two countries.

00:04:01.640 --> 00:04:05.020
And this exhibit started
as an exhibit, actually.

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:08.920
And then we couldn't raise enough
money for an exhibit as such.

00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:12.580 position:56%
So we decided to do a website, which
I think is much more interesting

00:04:12.580 --> 00:04:16.370
because it's going to be here
forever on the web, and --

00:04:16.370 --> 00:04:20.320 position:56%
so people from around the world will
be able to see these unique maps,

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:25.260
films, photographs, manuscripts --
especially prints and photographs

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:29.330
from all over the area that are
here in the Library's collections.

00:04:29.330 --> 00:04:31.630
And I want to thank very
much Barbara Tenenbaum

00:04:31.630 --> 00:04:34.040
and Everett Larsen [assumed
spelling] and Juan Manuel Perez

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:38.240
who spirited this wonderful
project with Tracy North.

00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:41.200
And so it took a lot of hard work.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:43.510
And with a number of interns,
whom I shall not mention

00:04:43.510 --> 00:04:45.580
because there're probably 20
different interns who worked

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:47.040
on it for -- over the years.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:49.430
And the Spanish version
was very much supported

00:04:49.430 --> 00:04:51.850
by the Mexican government
and the Embassy of Mexico.

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:55.400
And I will now introduce
you to Barbara Tenenbaum,

00:04:55.400 --> 00:04:58.420
the former Mexican specialist
of the Hispanic division,

00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:01.940
who is still a volunteer, so
we still see her all the time.

00:05:01.940 --> 00:05:03.240
And I don't want to close

00:05:03.240 --> 00:05:05.850
without thanking Beverly
Brennan [assumed spelling],

00:05:05.850 --> 00:05:08.770
Sarah Duke [assumed spelling],
[inaudible] Motion Pictures and all

00:05:08.770 --> 00:05:12.610
over the Library who've really
helped us with this exhibit.

00:05:12.610 --> 00:05:14.510
Barbara.

00:05:14.510 --> 00:05:24.950
[ Applause ]

00:05:24.950 --> 00:05:26.250
&gt;&gt; Barbara Tenenbaum:
Good afternoon.

00:05:26.250 --> 00:05:30.180
Thank you, David and Georgette.

00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:34.800
For Mexicans and for
people who love Mexico,

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:40.070
the 10th year of every
century is a momentous event

00:05:40.070 --> 00:05:43.560
because it commemorates both
the beginning of the movement

00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:48.050
for independence from
Spain in 1810 and the start

00:05:48.050 --> 00:05:52.980
of what would become the
Mexican Revolution in 1910.

00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:57.580
Given that the Library
itself was founded in 1800,

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:01.150
I assumed that we would
have very few items relating

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:02.940
to the Independence.

00:06:02.940 --> 00:06:07.200
So working on something concerning
the Mexican Revolution was an

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:09.340
obvious choice for us.

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:12.320
And it was a good choice,
since it turned

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:18.880
out that every single division
of this Library had something

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:20.950
about the Mexican Revolution.

00:06:20.950 --> 00:06:23.180
It was just absolutely amazing.

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:28.200
It's been a long road from my
first thoughts on how the Library

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:33.010
of Congress could celebrate these
events from an actual exhibition

00:06:33.010 --> 00:06:37.490
of some of the treasures
held here, to a website,

00:06:37.490 --> 00:06:44.520
to a bilingual website; the
first assembled by the library,

00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:47.440
assisted by a vital grant

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:50.670
from Mexico's Secretaria
de Relaciones Exteriores,

00:06:50.670 --> 00:06:54.240
better known as Mexico's
Foreign Ministry.

00:06:54.240 --> 00:07:02.160
Part of the reason the website
took a long time to complete was

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:10.680
that we found so much material
and with that so many surprises.

00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:14.900
Even observing copyright
restrictions that limited us

00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:22.500 position:56%
to material published by 1924 or so,
we still found lots of treasures.

00:07:22.500 --> 00:07:29.640 position:56%
For example, who knew that President
William Howard Taft would write his

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:34.950
beloved wife, Nellie, after
meeting President Porfirio Diaz

00:07:34.950 --> 00:07:38.330
for the first time --
and the last time --

00:07:38.330 --> 00:07:42.820
that he hoped that the Mexican
president would outlive him

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:44.700
because he didn't want
to have to deal

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:46.000
with what might come after that.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:47.300 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Carlos Manuel Sada Solana: Sorry.

00:07:47.300 --> 00:07:48.600
Sorry for interrupting.

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:51.580
&gt;&gt; Barbara Tenenbaum

00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:52.880
&gt;&gt; No, no, no.

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:55.180
Please.

00:08:01.330 --> 00:08:04.770
That the motion picture
division would have movies filmed

00:08:04.770 --> 00:08:09.470
on location during the
Mexican Revolution.

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:12.870
Who knew that Pancho Villa
didn't have battles at night

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:14.810
because they were impossible
to light?

00:08:14.810 --> 00:08:18.710
He made a contract with movie
companies so they could film him.

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:21.180
I mean, he was no fool.

00:08:21.180 --> 00:08:23.340
[ Laughter ]

00:08:23.340 --> 00:08:28.770
Who knew that the music
division would have sheet music

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:32.790
from the period, and
that some talented people

00:08:32.790 --> 00:08:37.040
on staff would bring
these tunes to life?

00:08:37.040 --> 00:08:41.900
Who knew that the manuscript
division would have original

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:48.270 position:56%
manuscripts by Brigido Caro who left
Mexico to live first in San Antonio

00:08:48.270 --> 00:08:52.850
and then to Los Angeles in
the manuscript division?

00:08:52.850 --> 00:08:57.540
We have six original
plays written by him.

00:08:58.670 --> 00:09:04.910
The site has already led
to Mexicans asking for copy

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:13.870
of Emilio Vazquez Gomez's La
Reeleccion Indefinida of 1890,

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:18.750
and we sent a copy of
the 18-paged document.

00:09:18.750 --> 00:09:20.400
Or that a professor looking

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:25.020
at Chicano Theater would happily
see the works of Brigido Caro

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:28.210
and get very excited that
he could actually read them

00:09:28.210 --> 00:09:33.120
in the manuscript division?

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:36.930
We are currently working
with El Colegio de Mexico

00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:41.140
to establish a two-month grant so
that a Mexican student can come

00:09:41.140 --> 00:09:45.120
to the Library and work on
the materials alluded to

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:47.600
and found on the website.

00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:51.740
We hope that this will lead to
greater and greater interaction

00:09:51.740 --> 00:09:55.780
between the Library of Congress --
the largest library in the world --

00:09:55.780 --> 00:09:59.380
and Mexican institutions
of higher learning.

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:05.670
Just as it takes a village
to raise a child, so, too,

00:10:05.670 --> 00:10:09.410
it takes many people -- and many
more because websites continue

00:10:09.410 --> 00:10:15.410
to live, not like books -- it takes
many people to complete a website.

00:10:15.410 --> 00:10:21.070
I would like to recognize just
a few: my chief, Georgette Dorn,

00:10:21.070 --> 00:10:24.490
my colleagues, Dr. Everett
Larsen [assumed spelling],

00:10:24.490 --> 00:10:28.450
Dr. Juan Manuel Perez,
and Tracy North.

