00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:14.740
I find the site very
easy to navigate.

00:14:14.740 --> 00:14:17.140
And like I said, I'd
like to have you join me

00:14:17.140 --> 00:14:19.770
on a stroll through the exhibition.

00:14:19.770 --> 00:14:25.460 position:56%
First, some of the special
materials that surround the objects.

00:14:25.460 --> 00:14:27.490
We have included a
timeline that begins

00:14:27.490 --> 00:14:33.490
with the 1908 Creelman interview
and goes through the early 1920s.

00:14:33.490 --> 00:14:37.290
We have a special feature
that offers an interactive map

00:14:37.290 --> 00:14:45.130
of the tragic ten days of a revolt
in February of 1913 in Mexico City.

00:14:45.130 --> 00:14:51.340 position:56%
Now up until this point, Mexico City
itself had been excluded from a lot

00:14:51.340 --> 00:14:53.370
of the battles of the Revolution.

00:14:53.370 --> 00:14:54.670
Not after this.

00:14:54.670 --> 00:14:58.520
So the way the interactive page
works, you click on a number

00:14:58.520 --> 00:15:02.640
and it takes you down to a
